    🌈 Quickstart¶

    This page shows how to load a time-series spectroscopic dataset, do some basic calculations with it, generate some visualizations, and then save it out to another format.

    In [1]:
    Copied! 
    from chromatic import read_rainbow, version
from chromatic import plt, np, u
    from chromatic import read_rainbow, version from chromatic import plt, np, u
    In [2]:
    Copied! 
    version()
    version()
    Out[2]:
    '0.3.1'

    The JWST Early Release Observation of WASP-96b is one of the first observations of a transiting exoplanet with a 6.5m infrared space telescope. Let's load the default pipeline x1dints outputs provided with these data; there are lots of reasons why we shouldn't use these particular pipeline files for science, but they're useful for a quick initial look.

    In [3]:
    Copied! 
    rainbow = read_rainbow(
    "example-datasets/stsci/jw02734002001_04101_00001-seg00*_nis_x1dints.fits"
)
    rainbow = read_rainbow( "example-datasets/stsci/jw02734002001_04101_00001-seg00*_nis_x1dints.fits" )
    ðŸŒˆ Warning: 
Loading NIRISS spectroscopic `order=1``. Three orders are available,
and you can set which (1,2,3) you want to read with the `order=` option.

ðŸŒˆ Warning: 
Times were set by linearly interpolating between the exposure
start and end points. It's very possible these times are off
by at least a few seconds and possibly up to the duration
of one integration (= 76.916s)

ðŸŒˆ Warning: 
The 2048 input wavelengths were not monotonically increasing.
<ðŸŒˆ(2048w, 280t)> has been sorted from lowest to highest wavelength.
If you want to recover the original wavelength order, the original
wavelength indices are available in `rainbow.original_wave_index`.

    To see a transit in these data, we'll can normalize out the median spectrum of the star and make a map of the flux over wavelength and time.

    In [8]:
    Copied! 
    rainbow.normalize().pcolormesh();
    rainbow.normalize().pcolormesh();

    What a transit! Let's bin these data to very low resolution ($R = \lambda/\Delta \lambda = 10$), fold the times onto the period and transit epoch for WASP-96b, and plot the data as a series of stacked transit light curves.

    In [9]:
    Copied! 
    (
    rainbow.normalize()
    .bin(R=10)
    .fold(period=3.4252577 * u.day, t0=2459111.30170 * u.day)
    .plot()
)
    ( rainbow.normalize() .bin(R=10) .fold(period=3.4252577 * u.day, t0=2459111.30170 * u.day) .plot() )
    Out[9]:
    <AxesSubplot:xlabel='Time from Mid-Transit ($\\mathrm{d}$)', ylabel='Relative Flux (+ offsets)'>

    Finally, let's convert these data into a different format by saving it as a new file, which we might imagine using as a starting place for another analysis.

    In [10]:
    Copied! 
    rainbow.save("example-datasets/chromatic/ero-transit-wasp-96b.rainbow.npy")
    rainbow.save("example-datasets/chromatic/ero-transit-wasp-96b.rainbow.npy")

    That's it! This quick tutorial highlighted chromatic's abilities to...

    • load in time-series spectra or multiwavelength light curves from formats like x1dints
    • access core data variables like wavelength, time, flux, uncertainty
    • perform calculations like normalize and .bin
    • visualize the data with reasonable default choices

    Hopefully, you're now curious to read through the User Guide to learn more about options for reading ðŸŒˆs, doing actions with ðŸŒˆs, visualizing ðŸŒˆs in different ways, and more!
